items.name: mouseyMIX-Pro
items.description:
This is mousymix, refined. This is mouseyMIX-Pro.

Mouseymix is an little known merge model from ClosertoDeath, who is a model-trainer who made some more well known merges, such as pastelmix, HoloKukiV2, or SomethingV2_2, possible. It is a powerful but finicky checkpoint, extremely overfit due to the nature of its construction, but unparalleled in affecting the style that it does. Its unique style that has inspired with more refined tastes to attempt leverage its strength while discarding its weaknesses through merging. Gyozamix. FantaStel. Osenayan, MIX-Pro. But inevitably they all diverge from mouseymix's unique style and strengths and begin to lose what makes mouseymix what it is. MIX-Pro-V4.5+Colorbox is the purest of the mouseymix descendants but inevitably even then, it cannot retain mousemix's pure style thanks to the amount of merges and changes needed to reduce the amount of overfitting in mousy.

But what if we just merged mouseymix back into MIX-Pro?

Utilizing new style-strip composition-retention block weights from cyberwaifuroon, mouseyMIX-Pro applies mousey-correction onto MIX-Pro, thereby allowing us to utilize MIX-Pro's fantastic versatility and responsiveness to prompts while retaining mouseymix's style. The result is a highly opinionated and powerful yet versatile style model that hewns more closely to mouseymix than other checkpoint besides mouseymix, itself.

MIX-Pro returns to Mousey. mouseyMIX-Pro.

Style-transfer proof-of-concept HuggingFace repository with block-merge weights

My Witcher LoRA Index - soul3142's Guide to the Witcher Universe. additionally you can check out some other characters i've made from other games also.

Main Trigger Word - eskelW3_soul3142 , check examples for other ones.

Recommendations :-

  1. Highres Fix - must, if you are getting blurry and ugly images

    My upscale method: txt2img 512x768 -> send to img2img -> controlnet tile upscale, tile diffusion 2x scale with 4xUltrasharp upscaler and tiled vae

  2. Weight: 0.6 - 0.8

  3. Clip Skip: 2

  4. Denoising - Don't go too high, it can alter a lot of details

I use 0.7 weight, 25 steps, Euler a, Clip skip 2 in nearly all my examples with almost same, simple +ve/-ve prompts regardless of checkpoint for my own consistency purposes.

There are imperfections here & there, which i usually leave it in as is, (i never do any inpainting in examples), most of which like hands can be fixed with better prompting, negative embeddings while other like weapons are just bad majority of the time no matter the model as of today.

Some LoRA's are flexible with any clothing, some are not (usually character's with single costume) so keep these things in mind.

This is an unofficial fanmade LoRA, not intended for any commercial purpose and use. All characters and IP rights are owned by their respective creators and owners. I do not own rights to any of these characters.

items.name: AutoChar - Easy character art creation with face auto-inpaint
items.description:
–°heck "About this version" notes to the right for full 0.9 changes info!

AutoChar Control Panel is a custom script for Stable Diffusion WebUI by Automatic1111 made to help newbies and enthusiasts alike achieve great pictures with less effort.
https://github.com/alexv0iceh/AutoChar

Basically, it's automation of my basic SD workflow for illustrations (check 'em here: https://t.me/dreamforge_tg) and also my Bachelor graduation work, for which I got an A. I've put decent emphasis in code readability and comments for it, so I hope it will help future contributors and developers of other scripts.

So, let us enjoy the open beta!

Installation

Just put script and latest .onnx face recognition model in your stable-diffusion-webui/scripts folder. PLEASE, don't try to install via URL, it's not an extension, it won't be visible this way!

How to use

1. Go to your txt2img tab

2. Write prompt, select basic parameters as usual (you don't need highres fix, since it's included in the algorithm)

3. Select "AutoChar Beta 0.9" in dropdown menu Scripts in the lower part of page

4. Click "Generate" and enjoy

WARNINGS

  • It's kind of conflicting with AfterDetailer and may cause crashes if used together

  • If it gives you FileNotFoundError, please, make sure your saving directories are divided by txt2img and img2img folders in /stable-diffusion-webui/output. You can do it it Settings-Paths for saving.

Functions and features as of now:

  • Automatic 2-stage upscale

  • Automatic face and eyes inpaint, for all detected faces on image

  • Custom filtering function to help reduce noise on first generation and raise sharpness of the image before upscaling

  • For even higher quality, you can toggle face and eyes inpaint in between upscaling steps with little impact on generation time

  • If you're really heavy on your LORA's usage, you can toggle CFG scale lowering for face inpaint to avoid burning

  • Fully compatible with ControlNet

  • Works in both txt2img and img2img (for img2img, it will use selected resolution as base, and Second upscale denoising strength in AutoChar's advanced settings, and ignore one selected in parameters of generation)

  • Added full support for Dynamic Prompts. Enjoy fully automatic enhancement for all of your randomized generations.

  • Added SD Upscale as a new default instead of basic Image2Image. Much greater detail and sharpness + customization with your preferred upscaler.

  • Lower LoRA: new measure to avoid burnout on faces when using strong or multiple LoRAs. On by default.

  • Biggest face: inpaints only the largest face on generation, no more abominable body horrors on armpits and breasts, also helps with crowdy pictures. On by default.

  • Now only first and last generation of each cycle will be saved to Txt2img output folder by default. All the other steps will be stored in Img2img folder.

Algorithm itself:

- Txt2img generation in chosen resolution

- High-res fix (default: x1.2 on 0.55 denoising strength) to boost details and gain sharpness

- [Optional, "on" by default] Filtering with chosen strength (default: 0.5, less is better for realistic or smooth-rendered images)

- [Optional, "off" by default] Automatic inpainting of face and eyes with chosen parameters (default: 0.2 denoising strength)

- Img2img (default: x1.5 from first generation on 0.3 denoising strength)

- Automatic inpainting of face and eyes with chosen parameters (default: 0.2 denoising strength)

Future functions, feel free to wait or suggest your code:

- Adding anime face recognition model (sadly, it will kinda break or make it less time efficient to upscale eyes)

- More elegant implementation for img2img (it works just fine now, but the inteface is the same when it should be different)

- Add automatic head area hightlighting with added contrast and brightness

- Move information from terminal to textbox in WebUI

- ControlNet fixation of first/second generation to preserve shapes through upscale better

- Selecting flat color for init image, would be great in achieving darker pictures with black or grey init, as well as setting color theme of image

- Integration of postprocessing extras upscale and custom effects, such as noise, vignette or watermarks

Coming in 1.0:

  • Release as full extension.

  • Full Img2Img support.

  • ControlNet integration.

  • More parameters for advanced users.

Known issues, feel free to suggest your fixes:

- Poor for using on anime arts, can't detect faces on them

- Doesn't pick up your selected Styles from menu automatically, you need to APPLY them to prompt first

- Don't select 4x-UltraSharp upscaler if you don't have one (if so, get it here https://mega.nz/folder/qZRBmaIY#nIG8KyWFcGNTuMX_XNbJ_g)

modelVersions.name: v0.9

Appreciate my work? My TIs are free, but you can always buy me a coffee. :)

Curious about my usual work process? I have summarized it here.

How to create a good prompt using my TIs

You're obviously free to experiment, but bear in mind that my TIs are trained with a more or less fixed phrasing, that normally starts with:

"photo of EMBEDDING_NAME, a woman"

So I recommend always starting your prompt like that and then building the rest of the prompt from there. For instance, "photo of beautiful (d4merd4sh:0.99), a woman as a movie star, freckles, sweater off-shoulders, trousers, at a movie premiere gala, dark moody ambience (masterpiece:1.2) (photorealistic:1.2) (bokeh) (best quality) (detailed skin:1.2) (intricate details) (nighttime) (8k) (HDR) (cinematic lighting) (sharp focus), (looking at the camera:1.1), (closeup portrait:1.1)"

items.name: Orc /  Goblin Attack - Surrounded by monsters
items.description:
After specializing in orc-related content, I wanted to share some tips for using LoRA models specifically for orcs. If you're interested in creating orc-inspired artwork or designs, I recommend using the Midnight Mixer Melt as the base model. This model works well when fine-tuned with orc-related embeddings.

For optimal results, you can use embeddings for orc characters such as Gr√ªmsh, Thrakgar, or Uzgosh. However, the model can also generate orc-like images without specific embeddings.

To enhance the vibrancy of colors, I suggest using the WD VAE. Additionally, it's important to set the CLIP skip to 2 to ensure smooth generation.

Weight recommendations for the LoRA model:

  • For v2_offset: between 1 and 0.6 (Only available if you are an orc)

  • For v2_original: between 0.5 and 0.3(Only available if you possess the ancient orcish language)

  • For v1: around 0.8

When using this model, make sure to include the trigger keyword "orcstyle" to generate orc-specific results. You can also try using keywords like "Gr√ªmsh" or "orc warrior" to further refine the generated content.

Please note that LoRA is intended to be used within the context of orc-related content. It is not a standalone model, and it is not designed for general image generation.

To use LoRA in the auto1111 framework, follow these steps:

  1. Update the webui by using "git pull" command or redownload it.

  2. Copy the LoRA file to the "stable-diffusion-webui/models/lora" directory.

  3. Select the LoRA model within the web interface, as shown in the accompanying video.

  4. If necessary, adjust the weight settings for optimal results. By default, the weight is set to 1.

While it may be possible to mix this approach with a Wano style embedding, I have not personally tested it, and it is unlikely to be necessary. Overall, this LoRA model produces cleaner results with fewer background artifacts or irregularities.

Enjoy exploring the world of orcs with LoRA and unleash your creativity! items.name: Daisy Keech (JG version)
items.description:
A request of @webman240130.

(I just realised my good friend @ElizaPottinger had already fulfilled this request... sorry about that, man! Please check his fantastic version here!)

Daisy Keech is a social media celebrity with around 6M followers on Instagram. This embedding is based on her pre-surgery looks. Nowadays she looks a bit different.

180-step TI trained on a dataset of 6 images with my usual settings.

Appreciate my work? My TIs are free, but you can always buy me a coffee. :)

Curious about my usual work process? I have summarized it here.

How to create a good prompt using my TIs

You're obviously free to experiment, but bear in mind that my TIs are trained with a more or less fixed phrasing, that normally starts with:

"photo of EMBEDDING_NAME, a woman"

So I recommend always starting your prompt like that and then building the rest of the prompt from there. For instance, "photo of beautiful (da1syk33ch:0.99), a woman as a movie star, freckles, sweater off-shoulders, trousers, at a movie premiere gala, dark moody ambience (masterpiece:1.2) (photorealistic:1.2) (bokeh) (best quality) (detailed skin:1.2) (intricate details) (nighttime) (8k) (HDR) (cinematic lighting) (sharp focus), (looking at the camera:1.1), (closeup portrait:1.1)"
